YUM (Yellowdog Updater Modified), an open source command-line as well as graphical based package management tool for RPM
RPM (RedHat Package Manager)
by Seth Vidal under GPL (General Public License)

System architecture
... repos setup around the web (url and .repo provided)
|
redhat centos repo setup /etc/yum.repo.d/*.repo 
|
cache, yum keeps all the repository enabled package data in /var/cache/yum/ with each sub-director
|
software installed

Repo management
Add repo
1. [repository] section to the /etc/yum.conf file
2. add a .repo file in the /etc/yum.repos.d/ directory. All files with the .repo file extension in this directory are read by yum, and it is recommended to define your repositories here instead of in /etc/yum.conf
3. Yum repositories commonly provide their own .repo file.
yum-config-manager --add-repo https://repository_url.repo

list repo
yum repolist (only enabled)
yum repolist all

enable/disable repo
yum-config-manager --enable/disable repository_id_from_yum_repolist
yum-config-manager --enable/disable glob_expressionâ€¦

remove repo
1 /etc/yum.conf 
2 remove .repo file 
3 disable it

Package management
Install
yum install package-name
yum install -y package-name 
yum install enablerepo=repo-name  package-name(install from target repo)

Uninstall
yum remove package-name
yum remove -y package-name

Update
yum check-updates (check is there're updates available)
yum update package-name (to actually update)
yum update (update all)

List
yum list package-name
yum list (all)
yum list installed (all installed)

Search
yum search word-in-package-name

View 
yum info package-name

Package group management
a package group is a bundle of packages
List
yum grouplist 

Install
yum groupinstall 'my group name'

Update 
yum groupupdate 'my group name'

Remove
yum groupremove 'my group name'

Cache management
yum clean all

Interactive
yum shell

After installation management
Files track, to check which package a specific file belongs to
yum provides /path/to/file

History of installations
yum history

Redhat subscription 
Portal  
|
Subscription management service 
|
managed systems

List pools
subscription-manager list --available
subscription-manager list --available --all

Register, tell service who it is
subscription-manager register

Unregister
subscription-manager unregister

Attach, tell servic
subscription-manager attach --auto
subscription-manager attach --pool=<POOL_ID>

Refresh
subscription-manager refresh

All in one
subscription-manager register --username <username> --password <password> --auto-attach

Clean up
subscription-manager clean


